sidebyside.p:
We substitute x=\alert{-1} into the equation for the circle, and solve for y.
\begin{align*} (\alert{-1}^2)+y^2 \amp = 4\\ y^2 \amp = 4-1 = 3\\ y \amp = \pm \sqrt{3}\\ \end{align*}
The points are (-1, \sqrt{3}) and (-1,\sqrt{3}), as shown at right. Note that \sqrt{3} \approx 1.732.

subsection.p:
An irrational number is one that cannot be written as a quotient of two integers ~~\dfrac{a}{b},~~\text{where}~~ b\not=0,~~.  Examples of irrational numbers are \sqrt{3}, \sqrt[3]{586}, and \pi.  The decimal form of an irrational number is nonterminating and nonrepeating.  The first few digits of the examples mentioned are

               \begin{align*}
               \sqrt{3} \amp = 1.732050807568...\\
               \sqrt[3]{586} \amp = 8.368209391204...\\ 
               \pi \amp = 3.141592653589...\\
               \end{align*}

sidebyside.p:
The radius of the pie is 4 inches, so its circumference is 2\pi (4) inches. A 60째 wedge, shown at right, is 
    \dfrac{1}{6} of the entire pie, so its edge is \dfrac{1}{6} of the circumference.  The exact length of the arc is thus 
 \dfrac{1}{6} (8\pi)=\dfrac{4\pi}{3} \text{ inches.}
